e spread of neoliberal ideology and its reliance on racism—marked by individualism, market competition, and privatization—these bastions of community support are losing the autonomy that has allowed them to embolden the minds of the youth they serve. Baldridge captures the stories of loss and resistance within this context of immense external political pressure, arguing powerfully for the damage caused when the same structural violence that Black youth experience in school, starts to occur in the places they go to escape it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aAfrican American youthxEducationzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aAfter-school programszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aCommunity and schoolzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aMinority youthxEducationzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aSocial work with youthzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aYouth workerszUnited StatesvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh  aBlack youth.  aafter-school.  acommunity-based education.  acommunity-based youth organizations.  aeducation privatization.  amarket-drive education reform.  aprivatization.  arace.  ayouth work.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology, Education, Psychology 2020z9783110704549oZDB-23-SEW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311069228040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360790340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503607903423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.